question.text: Which of the following best describes the energy conversion process of a battery operating in a remote controller?

explanation.concept_text: There are at least six types of energy students should know for the Canadian DAT. A battery is an electrochemical cell with a positive terminal ( cathode ) and a negative terminal ( anode ) that supplies electric power (dependent on its voltage ) by conducting electrons from anode to the cathode through the circuit it is connected to. The redox reaction in which a battery is supplying electric power is undergoing an energy conversion from chemical to electric due to a transfer of electrons from each half-cell (chemical) to provide current for the board (electrical). Therefore, the correct answer is Option A .

question.text: The point above which a gas cannot be converted into a liquid is known as what?

explanation.concept_text: The critical point is located at the end of the vaporization/condensation curve (blue line) between liquid phase and gas phase. Above this point contains a medium called supercritical fluid , in which it cannot be distinguished as liquid or solid and is merged as one (sometimes this is called plasma ). Thus, above the critical point, neither gas nor liquid can be converted from one to another. Therefore, the correct answer is Option D . CC By 4.0
explanation.poe_text: Option A. Triple point - This is the point at which all three phases exist together. Therefore, this choice is incorrect . Option B. End point - This is the point during a titration when an indicator shows a color change and has reached the equivalence point. Therefore, this choice is incorrect . Option C. Equivalence point - This is the point during a titration when the moles of titrant are equal to the moles of titrate (acid = base). Therefore, this choice is incorrect . Option E. Infection point - This is the point on a titration curve where the pK a or pK b can be determined. Therefore, this choice is incorrect .

question.text: Which of the following are the Bronsted-Lowry bases in the equilibrium below? CH 3 NH 2( aq ) + HCl ( aq ) ↔ CH 3 NH 3 + ( aq ) + Cl - ( aq )

explanation.concept_text: The Bronsted-Lowry acid-base theory focuses on the ability of a species to donate a proton (acid) or accept a proton (base). In the above reaction, one should turn the focus on both the reactant side and the product side and determine which one is the base in each half. In this reaction, HCl ( aq ) is the Bronsted-Lowry acid as it is donating an H + to CH 3 NH 2 ( aq ) [Bronsted-Lowry base] to form Cl – ( aq ) [conjugate base of HCl ( aq ) ] and CH 3 NH 3 + ( aq ) [conjugate acid of CH 3 NH 2 ( aq ) ]. Therefore, the correct answer is Option B .

question.text: Which of the following molecules produces an acidic solution when placed in water?

explanation.concept_text: There are three principles on how to determine the acidity, basicity, or neutrality of salt. In order to be able to master these types of questions, one must know the common weak acids and weak bases in general chemistry. 1. If both ions of salt are conjugate acid and conjugate base of a strong base and strong acid, respectively, then the salt will produce a neutral solution. 2. If cation of salt is conjugate acid of weak base, then it will produce an acidic solution: HA (aq) + H 2 O (l) ⇄ A - (aq) + H 3 O + (aq) 3. If anion of salt is conjugate base of a weak acid, then it will produce a basic solution: B (aq) + H 2 O (l) ⇄ HB + (aq) + OH - (aq) Using the information above, we can determine the answer by going through each option choice, as shown below. Therefore, the correct answer is Option C .
explanation.poe_text: Option A. NaCl - Na + = Neutral (NaOH) and Cl – = Neutral (HCl) → NaCl = Neutral Option B. KBr - K + = Neutral (KOH) and Br – = Neutral (HBr) → KBr = Neutral Option C. NH 4 Cl - NH 4 + = Acidic (NH 3 ) and Cl – = Neutral (HCl) → NH 4 Cl = Acidic Option D. LiF - Li + = Neutral (LiOH) and F – = Basic (HF) → LiF = Basic Option E. RbI - Rb + = Neutral (RbOH) and I – = Neutral (HI) → RbI = Neutral

question.text: Which substance reacts with water most violently to produce H 2 gas?

explanation.concept_text: For Canadian DAT, it is important to know that elements that are highly reducing (i.e., alkali metals and alkaline earth metals) are ones that are highly reactive in water. They react according to the following chemical equation. Alkali Metals: 2 M (s) + 2H 2 O (l) → 2 MOH (aq) + H 2 (g) Alkaline Earth Metals: M (s) +2 H 2 O (l) → M(OH) 2 (aq) + H 2 (g) The reason why these metals are highly reactive with water is that they will combust to form metal hydroxides and hydrogen gas, both of which will produce highly vigorous exothermic reaction when exposed to water vapor. Between the alkali metals and alkaline metals, alkali metals are more reactive. Therefore, the correct answer is Option E .

question.text: Which of the following enthalpy changes is correctly arranged from highest to lowest?

options.label: A.
options.text: ΔH° vaporization > ΔH° sublimation > ΔH° fusion

options.label: B.
options.text: ΔH° vaporization > ΔH° fusion > ΔH° sublimation

options.label: C.
options.text: ΔH° fusion > ΔH° sublimation > ΔH° vaporization

options.label: D.
options.text: ΔH° sublimation > ΔH° fusion > ΔH° vaporization

options.label: E.
options.text: ΔH° sublimation > ΔH° vaporization > ΔH° fusion

correct_answer_text: ΔH° sublimation > ΔH° vaporization > ΔH° fusion

explanation.concept_text: In a heating curve, a pure substance must overcome intermolecular forces in order to go through phase changes. There are two types of transitions when calculating the heat absorbed: calorimetry and enthalpy. Calorimetry corresponds to the portions of graph with sloped lines (single-phase: solid, liquid, gas). Enthalpy corresponds to portions of the graph with horizontal lines (phase transitions: melting (solid → liquid) and boiling (liquid → gas)). Because the boiling requires higher heat to be absorbed due to the complete dissolution of intermolecular forces than melting, . By Hess’s Law, sublimation is defined as the sum of vaporization and fusion, so it is the highest. Therefore, the correct answer is Option E . CC BY 4.0

question.text: Which of the following reaction is exothermic?

explanation.concept_text: Exothermic reactions are reactions or processes that release energy, usually in the form of heat or light. In an exothermic reaction, energy is released because the total energy of the products is less than the total energy of the reactants. Fusion , vaporization , and sublimation are endothermic processes, whereas freezing , condensation , and deposition are exothermic processes. Changes of state are examples of phase changes. It's important to know that all phase changes are accompanied by changes in the energy of a system. Changes from a more-ordered state to a less-ordered state (such as a liquid to a gas) are endothermic. Changes from a less-ordered state to a more-ordered state (such as a liquid to a solid) are always exothermic. The various phase changes can be seen in the diagram below. CC BY 4.0

question.text: Under which of the following conditions will a spontaneous process always occur?

explanation.concept_text: The equation that governs enthalpy, entropy, and free energy is indicated by: ΔG = ΔH -TΔS The only way for free energy to be negative (spontaneous) at all temperatures is when enthalpy is negative (exothermic) and entropy is positive (high). Since free energy is primarily dictated by enthalpy, the only way to prevent entropy from overcoming enthalpy is to have the entropic component (–TΔS) be negative at all temperatures, which requires ΔS to be positive as it is multiplied by negative T. This can be shown in the table below. Therefore, the correct answer is Option D .
explanation.poe_text: Option A. ΔH o < 0, ΔS o < 0 - This condition would lead to spontaneity only under low temperature. Therefore, this choice is incorrect . Option B. ΔH o > 0, ΔS o > 0 - This condition would lead to spontaneity only under high temperature. Therefore, this choice is incorrect . Option C. ΔH o > 0, ΔS o < 0 - This condition would never lead to spontaneity regardless of temperature. Therefore, this choice is incorrect . Option E. ΔH o = 0, ΔS o < 0 - This condition would lead to equilibrium. Therefore, this choice is incorrect .

question.text: Which of the following best describes signs of heat and internal energy if no work is done in a reaction but heat is lost?

explanation.concept_text: The First Law of Thermodynamics states that the sum of heat ( q ) and work ( w ) is equal to the change in internal energy ( E ). The guidelines for sign convention of work and heat are described below. Because no work is being done, w = 0, and if heat is lost, q < 0, the change in internal energy would be negative according to the First Law of Thermodynamics. Therefore, the correct answer is Option B .

question.text: Which of the following is a state function?

explanation.concept_text: A state function is defined as a unit that depends only on the change between initial and final states of a system. A path function is defined as a unit that depends only on the process by which the change occurs. Of all the option choices, only enthalpy is a state function, because it is solely dependent on the final and initial states (and therefore can be written with the delta sign). All other options choices are path functions that depend on the process by which the process is done. Therefore, the correct answer is Option A .

question.text: Which of the following changes shifts the equilibrium to the left? C ( s ) + O 2( g ) ↔ CO 2( g ) ΔH o = -393.5 kJ•mol -1

explanation.concept_text: This is an example of Le Chatelier’s principle , which states that the system will drive itself back towards equilibrium to counterbalance the change. There are four types of possible changes students should be familiar with on Canadian DAT. This reaction is exothermic. It has 1 mole of gas on the reactant side and 1 mole of gas on the product side. Therefore, the only ways to shift left would be to either increase concentration of products, decrease the concentration of reactants, or increase the temperature. Therefore, the correct answer is Option B .
explanation.poe_text: Option A. Decreasing temperature - This would cause a shift to the right because heat is a product and this is an exothermic reaction. Therefore, this choice is incorrect . Option C. Adding O 2(g) - This would cause a shift to the right because there is an increase in the concentration of reactants. Therefore, this choice is incorrect . Option D. Adding catalyst - This would cause no shift because kinetics is not a measurement of equilibrium. Therefore, this choice is incorrect . Option E. Increasing pressure - This would cause no shift because both sides have an equal number of moles of gas. Therefore, this choice is incorrect .

question.text: Nuclear decay of Uranium-133 produces Thorium-129. Which type of decay has occurred?

explanation.concept_text: Radioactive decay is a process that occurs in unstable atomic nuclei. Different types of decay may occur depending on if there is an excess of neutrons, protons, or both. The various types of radioactive decay are summarized in the table below: CC BY 4.0
explanation.poe_text: Option A. Electron capture – This option is incorrect because electron capture only converts a proton into a neutron so there is no change in atomic mass as indicated in this question. The conversion of one nucleus into another is solely caused by radioactive decay. Option B. Beta decay – This option is incorrect because beta decay only converts a neutron into a proton so there is no change in atomic mass as indicated in this question. Option C. Positron emission – This option is incorrect because positron emission, like electron capture, only converts a proton into a neutron so there is no change in atomic mass as indicated in this question. This decay occurs when there is an excess of energy.

question.text: Consider the complex ion [Mn(CN) 6 ] 3- . What is the oxidation number of manganese?

explanation.concept_text: In order to determine the oxidation state, a set of general rules must be applied. The basic guidelines for oxidation states are: STEP 1: The rule regarding ions must be used as a starting point for this problem. Cyanide, a common polyatomic ion that should be known for the Canadian DAT, has a charge of -1. Therefore, the complete negative component of the complex ion in the question stem is -6 since there are six of these negatively charged ions: (6) * (-1) = -6 STEP 2: Knowing the overall charge of the complex ion (-3) and the overall negative component of the cyanide ions (-6), a simple algebra equation must be used to solve the charge of manganese to balance the ion: (-6) + Mn = (-3) Mn = (-3) + (+6) Mn = (+3) Therefore, the oxidation number of manganese is +3.

question.text: Which of the following molecules possesses a non-zero dipole moment?

explanation.concept_text: In order to determine if a molecule has a non-zero dipole moment, it must be determined if the bonds themselves have a dipole moment. This means that the two atoms must have a difference in electronegativity of 0.4 to 1.8 so that one molecule pulls on electrons harder than the other but is not pulling so strongly that the bond becomes ionic. STEP 1: In the case of NH 3 , or ammonia, nitrogen has an electronegativity of about 3.0 while hydrogen is about 2.1. Therefore, the electronegativity difference is 0.9 (3.0 – 2.9). Since 0.9 falls between 0.4 and 1.8, the first criteria is met. STEP 2: Now, it must be confirmed that the dipole moments are not geographically balanced, otherwise the overall molecule would not be polar. A Lewis structure of the eight valence electrons (five from nitrogen, one from each of the three hydrogens) from ammonia can be built, displaying that nitrogen does not need double or triple bonds and can thus remain in a tetrahedral shape: Step 3: Finally, it can be seen that the lone pair of electrons is not geographically balanced with another lone pair across from it and therefore the overall molecule is polar.
explanation.poe_text: Option A. BF 3 - This option is incorrect because there is geographic balance for the polar bonds. The electronegativity difference between boron (2.0) and fluorine (4.0) gives the bonds a polar character (4.0 - 2.0 = 2.0 > 1.8), but the molecule is trigonal planar with three identical groups. Therefore, the bonds all cancel each other out as they pull equally in opposing directions. Option B. Si(CH 3 ) 4 - This option is incorrect because there is no net dipole in the molecule since the four methyl groups all pull equally in four geographically opposing directions. Therefore, although the carbon (2.5) and silane (1.8) atoms have an electronegativity difference that makes them polar (2.5 – 1.8 = 0.7 > 0.4), the overall molecule does not have a dipole moment as the identical side groups of the tetrahedral shape pull equally in 4 different directions. Option C. CO 2 - This option is incorrect because the molecule is linear with identical side groups on the carbon, therefore the dipole moments of the bonds are pulled in geographically opposing directions and cancel each other out. The individual bonds between oxygen (3.5) and carbon (2.5) are polar (3.5 – 2.5 = 1.0 > 0.4). Option E. C 6 H 6 - This option is incorrect because this formula indicates benzene which is made up of all carbon and hydrogen atoms. Carbon to carbon bonds have no electronegativity difference and carbon (2.5) to hydrogen (2.1) bonds are not polar as their electronegativity difference is not greater than 0.4 (2.5 – 2.1 = 0.4). Therefore, the molecule cannot have an overall dipole moment.

question.text: Which of the following is the correct the hybridization of a central carbon in propene, C 3 H 6 ?

explanation.concept_text: STEP 1: First, let's determine the structure for propene . The “prop-” prefix indicates that this is three carbons long while the “-ene” suffix alludes to the presence of a double bond. This yields the following structure: STEP 2: Next, count the number of atoms connected to it (atoms – not bonds!) . Looking at the image above, there are 3 atoms connected to the central carbon. STEP 3: Count the number of lone pairs attached to it. For propene, there are 0 lone pairs attached to the central carbon. STEP 4: Finally, add the two numbers together, and determine the hybridization according to the following rules: Sum of 4 = your atom is sp 3 Sum of 3 = your atom is sp 2 Sum of 2 = your atom is sp For the central atom in propene, the sum is: 3 atoms + 0 lone pairs = 3 Therefore, the correct answer is sp 2 hybridization.

question.text: For S 2- , Cl - , K + , Ca 2+ , which of the following is the correct ranking of ions from largest to smallest radius?

explanation.concept_text: Among isoelectronic species , atoms or ions that share the same electronic configuration, the primary difference is the number of protons in each species. Higher atomic number species have more protons so they will attract electrons more tightly than another isoelectronic species with fewer protons which decreases their radii. More quantitatively, the difference between isoelectronic species is their effective nuclear charge, Z eff . This is defined as the net positive charge that electrons feel and is equal to the number of protons minus the shielding constant which is generally related to the number of inner electrons. Since isoelectronic species have the same electronic configuration, the shielding constant is comparable among isoelectronic species. Thus, the main factor to consider in determining the relative size of electronic species members is the number of protons. Therefore, the correct answer is Option E. S 2- > Cl - > K + > Ca 2+ .
explanation.poe_text: Option A. is incorrect because as isoelectronic species to argon, Cl - must be smaller than S 2- due to having more protons and thus higher effective nuclear charge. Option B. is incorrect because as isoelectronic species to argon, Ca 2+ must be smaller than K + due to having more protons and thus higher effective nuclear charge. Option C. is incorrect because as isoelectronic species to argon, Ca 2+ must be smaller than S 2- due to having more protons and thus higher effective nuclear charge. Option D. is incorrect because as isoelectronic species to argon, Ca 2+ must be smaller than Cl - due to having more protons and thus higher effective nuclear charge.

question.text: Which of the following is emitted in the following decay reaction:

explanation.concept_text: Electron is the particle released in a beta decay reaction. In this reaction type, a neutron is converted to a proton and subsequently releases an electron. In this reaction type, the original nucleus undergoes no change in atomic mass, but increases by a value of one in atomic number:
explanation.poe_text: Option A. Positron - This option is incorrect because the loss of a positron would cause a decrease in atomic number. In this type of decay, a proton is converted to a neutron and consequently releases a positron. Atomic mass is unchanged. Option B. Gamma ray - This option is incorrect because gamma rays (γ) do not contain any mass and therefore their loss does not affect the overall mass of the nucleus. In gamma decay, the nucleus moves from an excited state (*) to a non-excited state. Option C. Helium nucleus - This option is incorrect because a helium nucleus decay pattern would result in a decrease in the atomic mass by 4 and a decrease in the atomic number by 2. The loss of a helium nucleus ( 4 / 2 He) is known as alpha decay. Option E. Proton - This option is incorrect because the loss of a proton ( 1 / 1 H) would result in a loss of one for the values of the atomic number and atomic mass rather than atomic number alone. Proton emission is rare form of radiation.

question.text: The theoretical yield of a combustion reaction is 19 g of H 2 O. Which of the following is the percent yield if 9 g of H 2 O was obtained?

explanation.concept_text: Theoretical yield is the amount of expected product based on stoichiometric calculations of the number of reactants. Percent yield is determined by creating the fraction: (experimental yield) / (theoretical yield) and multiplying the entire value by 100% in order to change it from a fraction or decimal value to a percentage. In this combustion reaction, the products are water and carbon dioxide. There is less water obtained than predicted by stoichiometry which translates to an answer that has a fraction with a smaller numerator and larger denominator.

question.text: Samples analyzed from a variety of sources possess the same ratio of elements chemically bonded together within each sample. Which of the following describes these samples?

explanation.concept_text: A compound is a substance composed of multiple elements that are found in a fixed stoichiometric ratio (e.g. H 2 O). The same compound will always posses the same ratio of elements chemically bonded together, regardless of where they are obtained. The question’s requirement of multiple atom types chemically bonded in fixed ratios of constituents are all satisfied by this answer. The image below shows the different types of substances and mixtures: CC BY 4.0
explanation.poe_text: Option A. Colloid - This option is incorrect because the ratio of elements is not fixed among different colloids. This term describes a type of mixture in which an immiscible element type is suspended evenly and uniformly in a dispersing medium (e.g. milk fats suspended in water). The composition of different colloids (e.g. brands of milk) is rarely identical. Option C. Heterogenous mixture - This option is incorrect because solutes in this mixture type are not uniformly dispersed. For example, if a chocolate chip cookie was sampled by cutting it into fourths, each piece would have a different composition (e.g. number of chocolate chips per quarter). Option D. Pure element - This option is incorrect because pure elements only possess one atom type rather than multiple. An example of a pure element is diamond, which is composed of only carbon. Option E. Homogenous mixture - This option is incorrect because samples of homogenous mixtures, although may contain identical constituents, are not chemically bonded together. For example, when salt is dissolved in water, the Na + and Cl - are not chemically bonded together with H 2 O – instead they interact through ion-dipole intermolecular interactions.
